{"actual_usd":0.158545,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":185,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31154,"reply":"\"I don't think it works that automatically.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square, buying half a beat to say it cleanly.* \"Christ's death is sufficient for all, yeah—but Scripture doesn't talk like everybody is saved regardless of whether they receive him.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"The way I've heard it plainest is: the gift is truly offered to all, but not everybody accepts the gift. So the problem isn't any shortage in Christ—it's real rejection. And rejection matters, because love doesn't force itself in.\"\n\n\"Now, Christians argue about some of the mechanics there—who can come, how grace works, all that.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"But no orthodox version lands at 'therefore everybody is automatically saved in the end' just from the fact that Christ died for the world.\"\n\n\"What part is catching at you most?\"","rolling_24h_usd":51.299650000000035,"run_id":"62d27fac-e8fc-4ce3-aec5-180183d0d265"}
